<TEXTAREA NAME="ReplyMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">[QUOTE]Originally posted by Alrik Fassbauer:
[I] The Problem with that is much more complicated.

Before I became a Forummember here, and that was back in 1999, when  :div: was just arisen as "Project C", I thought exactly the same as you do.

However, through all these years being a member in this Community, I learned A LOT about the Gaming Industry. And about all that's related to Larian Studios.

The sentence "If they can get it right with a patch, they can get it right before release" makes sense if you look naively at the Developing as such.

However, if you pay a closer look at [i]scheduling[/i], you might notice that there is something wrong with that Point of View.

With  :div: for example, you can follow this scheduling:

0. Publisher pressures to get Game ready at a [i]specific[/i] Date, no matter if this is Bugfree then, or not.
1. Get Game ready for Release.
2. Send Master Copy to CDV.
3. CDV sends Master Copy to the Manufacturing Company, aka "going Gold".
4. Four weeks later (or so) the Package is ready to buy.

Guess what happened [i]meanwhile[/i] ?  ;) Of course there was more testing, it simply hadn't stopped since sending the Master to CDV !  ;)

So, [i]meanwhile[/i] the production was running, [i]testing[/i] revealed some more Bugs. Many more Bugs, in this case.

The really bad thing about that is, when a Publisher doesn't have the Patience simply to [i]wait[/i]. Then, the Publisher demands that the Product [b]must[/b] be sold, no matter, if it is Bug-Free or not  [!]

A Procuct scheduling goes with the so-called "Milestones" (maybe you heard of them in conjunction with Mozilla), and a Milestonde is a certain [i]Date[/i], when a part of Software should be ready, or at least should have reached a definited state.

The very Last of these Dates ist the Date when a Game goes as the Master Copy to the Publisher.

And if the Publisher [b]wants[/b] the Software at this specific date, the Developing Company must deliver it ("stand and deliver !"  ;) ). Sadly, it is at this Point a kind of "Master and Servant".

So much of my thought about this matter here.  ;)

[/I][/QUOTE]

</TEXTAREA>
